 I John B. Jones, of Co.  41st Regt., Va. Vols., who was wounded is in any private of public hospital in the city of Richmond, the managers will oblige his brother very much believing his name at this office.

I will pay any amount of money to any one who will give me the desired information.

W. S. R. Jone;

 ordered, That Receivers Thos. T. Giles, Hery L. Brook, John T. Francis, Francis L. Smith, Jno. M. Seged. t. H. Camerell, and Wm. A. Maury, do each of them, on 16th June next, render before William F. Walson, a Commissioner of this Court, an account of all matters in his hands or under his control as Receiver as aforesaid, appointed under the act of Congress entitled, "An act for the sequestration of the estates, ] property, and efects of allen enemies, and for the indemulty of citizens of the Confederate States, and persons aiding the same in the existing war with the United States," approved August 30th, 1861, and do make and state an account and settlement under oath of his collections of moneys and disbursements, under the act aforesaid.

And it is further ordered, that the Marshal of this Court cause to be published in the Richmond, for four weeks consecutively before the said day of settlement, a copy of this order; and that the Clerk of the Court send a copy of each of said newspapers to the District Attory of the Confederate States for this District.

